[
    {
        "content": "<p>To what extent is it considered desirable to mimic the existing terminological expectations of a given field?</p>\n<p>The reason why I ask is that generally speaking the majority of mathematicians who actually use the word 'ordinal' are going to be expecting it to be a canonical representative of a given isomorphism class of well-order types, rather than the isomorphism type itself.</p>",
        "id": 576329565,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772218296
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think that's an entirely orthogonal discussion to the one I'm proposing. But if you want my opinion I think redefining ordinals as the subtype <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ZFSet.IsOrdinal#doc\">docs#ZFSet.IsOrdinal</a> would do much more harm than good.</p>",
        "id": 576361574,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hern√°ndez",
        "timestamp": 1772232378
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hern√°ndez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Unbundled.20relations.20and.20ordinal.20API/near/576361574\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think that's an entirely orthogonal discussion to the one I'm proposing. But if you want my opinion I think redefining ordinals as the subtype <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ZFSet.IsOrdinal#doc\">docs#ZFSet.IsOrdinal</a> would do much more harm than good.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I was not suggesting that. I'm just saying that the thing that is currently called <code>Ordinal</code> in Mathlib is closer to what I would call a 'well-order type' (as in an isomorphism class of well-orders) and the output of <code>Ordinal.ToType</code> is closer to what I would call an 'ordinal'.</p>",
        "id": 576371865,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772239863
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Since the cardinals is the quotient of sets under isomorphism, having the ordinals be the quotient of well ordered sets under isomorphism seems like a natural choice to me</p>",
        "id": 576372299,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1772240123
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not saying it's not a reasonable choice. I'm saying it doesn't line up with the way people use the word in practice, which is why I asked \"To what extent is it considered desirable to mimic the existing terminological expectations of a given field?\"</p>",
        "id": 576372509,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772240261
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>4 messages were moved here from <a class=\"stream-topic\" data-stream-id=\"287929\" href=\"/#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Unbundled.20relations.20and.20ordinal.20API/with/576329565\">#mathlib4 &gt; Unbundled relations and ordinal API</a> by <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hern√°ndez</span>.</p>",
