        "timestamp": 1772246820
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"904624\">James E Hanson</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576371865\">ha dicho</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hern√°ndez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Unbundled.20relations.20and.20ordinal.20API/near/576361574\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think that's an entirely orthogonal discussion to the one I'm proposing. But if you want my opinion I think redefining ordinals as the subtype <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ZFSet.IsOrdinal#doc\">docs#ZFSet.IsOrdinal</a> would do much more harm than good.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I was not suggesting that. I'm just saying that the thing that is currently called <code>Ordinal</code> in Mathlib is closer to what I would call a 'well-order type' (as in an isomorphism class of well-orders) and the output of <code>Ordinal.ToType</code> is closer to what I would call an 'ordinal'.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I think there's a more general tendency in pen and paper mathematics to try and understand quotients by giving some \"canonical\" representative out of each class. This is why you often see ‚Ñ§/n‚Ñ§ described as \"the numbers from 0 to n - 1\", or why a group theory argument might start with \"take an element out of each coset\". We just find it easier to think of a single element, rather than a whole family of elements with some common property.</p>\n<p>The same often happens to ordinals. Be it for technical or didactical reasons, one often defines an ordinal as a transitive ZFC set, well-ordered under membership. And that ensures that every ordinal corresponds to a single \"canonical\" linear order.</p>\n<p>But I'd argue the benefit of doing this, at least within Lean's theory, is quite slim. By the point you're defining addition, you have to contend that <code>x + y</code> isn't really the lexicographic sum of <code>x</code> and <code>y</code>, but rather whichever ordinal that's isomorphic to it. And something similar ends up happening with all of the other arithmetic operations. Your initial choice of representative ends up not mattering at all.</p>",
        "id": 576382613,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hern√°ndez",
        "timestamp": 1772247349
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>To answer your more general question, I think Mathlib is generally comfortable with deviating from the literature if it ends up making things simpler or more general. Another example within set theory: <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Cardinal.aleph#doc\">docs#Cardinal.aleph</a> is defined in terms of some made up <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Cardinal.preAleph#doc\">docs#Cardinal.preAleph</a>. This doesn't appear in the literature, but being the proper order isomorphism between ordinals and cardinals, it makes proving its basic properties much simpler.</p>",
        "id": 576382947,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hern√°ndez",
        "timestamp": 1772247645
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hern√°ndez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576382613\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>And that ensures that every ordinal corresponds to a single \"canonical\" linear order.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Why are you putting the word 'canonical' in quotes here? It is a canonical choice.</p>",
        "id": 576384754,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772249160
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hern√°ndez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576382613\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This is why you often see ‚Ñ§/n‚Ñ§ described as \"the numbers from 0 to n - 1\",</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/ZMod/Defs.html#ZMod\">But this is how it's done in Mathlib.</a></p>",
        "id": 576384802,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772249217
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"904624\">James E Hanson</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576384802\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hern√°ndez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576382613\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This is why you often see ‚Ñ§/n‚Ñ§ described as \"the numbers from 0 to n - 1\",</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/ZMod/Defs.html#ZMod\">But this is how it's done in Mathlib.</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>that's because it produces better definitional properties (two closed terms of <code>ZMod n</code> are equal iff they are definitionally equal)</p>",
        "id": 576385484,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1772249732
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"904624\">James E Hanson</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576384754\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hern√°ndez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576382613\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>And that ensures that every ordinal corresponds to a single \"canonical\" linear order.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Why are you putting the word 'canonical' in quotes here? It is a canonical choice.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>There is no canonical choice from Lean's type theory point of view, only a choice up to an isomorphism.</p>",
        "id": 576385697,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1772249931
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"214703\">Yury G. Kudryashov</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576385697\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"904624\">James E Hanson</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576384754\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hern√°ndez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576382613\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>And that ensures that every ordinal corresponds to a single \"canonical\" linear order.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Why are you putting the word 'canonical' in quotes here? It is a canonical choice.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>There is no canonical choice from Lean's type theory point of view, only a choice up to an isomorphism.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I don't necessarily think this would be a good definition (specifically because of universe issues), but in what way is <code>{Œ≤ : Ordinal // Œ≤ &lt; Œ±}</code> not a canonical realization of the order type of <code>Œ±</code>?</p>",
        "id": 576386613,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772250938
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also in the sentence I quoted, Violeta was talking about ordinals in the context of ZFC, not in the context of Lean.</p>",
        "id": 576386904,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772251265
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hern√°ndez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576382613\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>By the point you're defining addition, you have to contend that <code>x + y</code> isn't really the lexicographic sum of <code>x</code> and <code>y</code>, but rather whichever ordinal that's isomorphic to it.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Ordinal addition is often defined by transfinite recursion and then it's shown as a theorem that <code>x + y</code> is isomorphic to the order sum of <code>x</code> and <code>y</code>.</p>",
        "id": 576387478,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772251733
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Would either of you care to explain what's <span aria-label=\"sad\" class=\"emoji emoji-2639\" role=\"img\" title=\"sad\">:sad:</span> about that?</p>",
        "id": 576387556,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772251834
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I just don't like that definition very much anymore</p>",
        "id": 576388161,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1772252522
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if I had to come up with a concrete objection then how about \"it doesn't generalize to transfinite sums\" (at least I don't think it does)</p>",
        "id": 576388201,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1772252555
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And it can't be used for general order type addition ,  so going by the lexicographic sum method seemed more natural to me. What is the benefit of defining it via transfinite recursion? ( are we still talking about inside ZFC? )</p>",
        "id": 576389584,
        "sender_full_name": "Yan Yablonovskiy üá∫üá¶",
        "timestamp": 1772253913
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"773147\">Yan Yablonovskiy üá∫üá¶</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576389584\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>And it can't be used for general order type addition ,  so going by the lexicographic sum method seemed more natural to me. What is the benefit of defining it via transfinite recursion? ( are we still talking about inside ZFC? )</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This is not really a strong argument, but it fits into the general framework of transfinite recursion and works as a basic example. You do a lot of stuff with transfinite recursion in set theory, most of which doesn't seem to be doable with these kinds of definitions.</p>",
        "id": 576390618,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772254959
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"816344\">Aaron Liu</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576388201\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>if I had to come up with a concrete objection then how about \"it doesn't generalize to transfinite sums\" (at least I don't think it does)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It can be, although I wouldn't claim it's a cleaner definition. You define it by transfinite recursion with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mo>‚àë</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>Œ≤</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mi>Œ±</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>sup</mi><mo>‚Å°</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>Œ≥</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>Œ≤</mi></mrow></msub><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">(</mo><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">(</mo><msub><mo>‚àë</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>Œ≥</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mi>Œ±</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo fence=\"true\">)</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Œ±</mi><mi>Œ≥</mi></msub><mo fence=\"true\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\sum_{i &lt; \\beta} \\alpha_i = \\sup_{\\gamma &lt; \\beta} \\left(\\left(\\sum_{i &lt; \\gamma} \\alpha_i\\right) + \\alpha_\\gamma\\right)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1858em;vertical-align:-0.4358em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:0em;\">‚àë</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1864em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05278em;\">Œ≤</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.4358em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">Œ±</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3117em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0037em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.8em;vertical-align:-0.65em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop\">sup</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.242em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4559em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05556em;\">Œ≥</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05278em;\">Œ≤</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3802em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\"><span class=\"delimsizing size2\">(</span></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\"><span class=\"delimsizing size2\">(</span></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:0em;\">‚àë</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.162em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05556em;\">Œ≥</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.4358em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">Œ±</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3117em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0037em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\"><span class=\"delimsizing size2\">)</span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">Œ±</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0037em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05556em;\">Œ≥</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\"><span class=\"delimsizing size2\">)</span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 576390761,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772255115
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>it really feels like you're hiding the intuition, which is a lexographic sum, behind some transfinite recursion for essentially no reason</p>",
        "id": 576390937,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1772255310
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There are a lot of different constructions in set theory that are essentially transfinite compositions of operations, such as the definition of various inner models and iterated forcing extensions. At some point the correct intuition is transfinite recursion.</p>",
        "id": 576391605,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772256036
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The definition I wrote is just a compact way of saying that a transfinite sum of ordinals is transfinitely composing the operation of ordinal addition.</p>",
        "id": 576391684,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772256122
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It would probably be more conventionally written like this:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mo>‚àë</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mi>Œ±</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\sum_{i &lt; 0} \\alpha_i = 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0771em;vertical-align:-0.3271em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:0em;\">‚àë</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.162em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3271em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">Œ±</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3117em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0037em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><spa