    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is a direct generalization of defining finite sums in terms of <code>foldr</code>, conceptually speaking.</p>",
        "id": 576391922,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772256411
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"904624\">James E Hanson</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576387556\">ha dicho</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Would either of you care to explain what's <span aria-label=\"sad\" class=\"emoji emoji-2639\" role=\"img\" title=\"sad\">:sad:</span> about that?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This is just a matter of taste, but I don't like limit recursion very much. It means you always have to consider three different cases separately. And often, if you put in some thought, you can find a better definition which only splits up one or two cases.</p>",
        "id": 576392800,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hern√°ndez",
        "timestamp": 1772257411
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hern√°ndez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576392800\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"904624\">James E Hanson</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576387556\">ha dicho</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Would either of you care to explain what's <span aria-label=\"sad\" class=\"emoji emoji-2639\" role=\"img\" title=\"sad\">:sad:</span> about that?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This is just a matter of taste, but I don't like limit recursion very much. It means you always have to consider three different cases separately. And often, if you put in some thought, you can find a better definition which only splits up one or two cases.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>You can often get it down to just one case. <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Œ±</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>Œ≤</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>sup</mi><mo>‚Å°</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>Œ≥</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>Œ≤</mi></mrow></msub><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">(</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>Œ±</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>Œ≥</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo fence=\"true\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha + \\beta = \\sup_{\\gamma &lt; \\beta} \\left((\\alpha + \\gamma) + 1\\right)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">Œ±</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05278em;\">Œ≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1302em;vertical-align:-0.3802em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop\">sup</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.242em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4559em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05556em;\">Œ≥</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05278em;\">Œ≤</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3802em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">(</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">Œ±</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05556em;\">Œ≥</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">)</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 576392975,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772257564
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, that's what I was about to say. I was also going to bring up <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ZFSet.vonNeumann#doc\">docs#ZFSet.vonNeumann</a> and <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Cardinal.beth#doc\">docs#Cardinal.beth</a> where I managed to find definitions without the standard case splitting.</p>",
        "id": 576393058,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hern√°ndez",
        "timestamp": 1772257645
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"773147\">Yan Yablonovskiy üá∫üá¶</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576389584\">ha dicho</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>And it can't be used for general order type addition ,  so going by the lexicographic sum method seemed more natural to me. What is the benefit of defining it via transfinite recursion? ( are we still talking about inside ZFC? )</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I guess it's worth bringing up our plans to eventually redefine <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Ordinal#doc\">docs#Ordinal</a> as a subtype of <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=OrderType#doc\">docs#OrderType</a>.</p>",
        "id": 576393140,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hern√°ndez",
        "timestamp": 1772257739
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hern√°ndez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Definition.20of.20ordinals/near/576393058\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Yeah, that's what I was about to say. I was also going to bring up <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ZFSet.vonNeumann#doc\">docs#ZFSet.vonNeumann</a> and <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Cardinal.beth#doc\">docs#Cardinal.beth</a> where I managed to find definitions without the standard case splitting.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This is pretty common in constructive set theory (where you can't do the zero/successor/limit case split). That said, there are a fair number of definitions by transfinite recursion where you really do need to treat limits (or certain limits) specially.</p>",
        "id": 576393402,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772258003
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't really see this as that different from how many many proofs by induction on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{N}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">N</span></span></span></span> need to treat <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span> as a special case.</p>",
        "id": 576393421,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1772258024
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I do also complain when I see inductive proofs separate the zero case when a strong induction would suffice.</p>",
        "id": 576393451,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hern√°ndez",
        "timestamp": 1772258060
    }
]